These tells about what type of data a variable can store.These are 2 types.1.primitive 2.non-primitive data types
PRIMITIVE DATA TYPES:
1.byte  - 1 byte(8 bits), Range:-128 to 127, Ex:hours,min,sec,months etc...
2.short - 2 bytes(16bits), Range:-32768 to 32767, Ex:year,no.of students in school etc...
3.int   - 4 bytes(32 bits), Range : -2147483648 to 2147483647 , Ex: avg salary, towns population etc...
4.long  - 8 bytes(64 bits), Range : -9,223,372,036,854,775,808 to +9,223,372,036,854,775,807 Ex: ph no,adhar no etc...
5.float - 4 bytes(32 bits) , Range: upto 5-7 digits after decimal Ex;height,weight,temp etc...
6.double -8 bytes(64 bits) ,Range: upto 13-15 digits after decimal Ex:sceintific calculations etc...
7.char  - 2 bytes(16bits), Ex: Gender(M/F)
8.boolean -memory is depends upon the type of JVM;(yes/N0)

TYPE CASTING -Converting one data type to another data type
1.Implicit/Widening TC-Coverting a smaller data type into a bigger one, it will automatically compiler will converts it
2.Explicit/Narrowing TC-Coverting a bigger data type into a smaller one,it happens only when programmer externally instructs compiler
to perfor, conversion. It results in loss of memory

DEFUALT VALUES FOR DATATYPES
public class program {
    private static byte b;
    private static short s;
    private static int i;
    private static long l;
    private static char c;
    private static boolean bool;
    private static  float f;
    private static double d;
   
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(b);   //0
        System.out.println(s);    //0
        System.out.println(i);   //0
        System.out.println(l);   //0
        System.out.println(c);
        System.out.println(bool);   //false
        System.out.println(f);    //0.0
        System.out.println(d);  //0.0
    }
}
